"# Appendix E — Loops, and why they underpin everything

Every chapter of this book mentions a loop somewhere. This appendix
gathers them all in one place, adds the Scheme-specific idea that
recursion and iteration are the same thing, and makes the case that
the loop is the biggest pattern in the whole book.

## Every loop the book named

- **Chapter 1** — The tally counter is a loop. Each event carves a
  notch. Same operation each time.
- **Chapter 2** — Boolean logic itself has no loop. But feeding a
  Boolean expression back into itself creates one. That is where
  memory begins.
- **Chapter 3** — A relay is a switch. But relays wired in feedback
  form the first sequential logic. Feedback = loop.
- **Chapter 4** — Chip manufacturing is a decades-long loop. Each
  Moore's-law generation is one turn.
- **Chapter 5** — Combinational gates don't loop by themselves. But
  they are the substrate on which every loop is eventually built.
- **Chapter 6** — The full adder as a component doesn't loop. But its
  carry-out feeds the carry-in of the next column: the ripple loop.
- **Chapter 7** — The 4-bit adder's ripple **is** the loop, written
  in space in silicon and in time in Scheme.
- **Chapter 8** — The SR latch is a wire that literally goes in a
  loop. Memory lives on that loop.
- **Chapter 9** — The counter increments every clock tick. Loop
  incarnate.
- **Chapter 10** — Every state machine has a driver loop: read
  input, transition, emit, repeat.
- **Chapter 11** — The ALU by itself is combinational. But it lives
  inside the CPU's execute loop.
- **Chapter 12** — The fetch-decode-execute loop. The biggest loop in
  the book. Every action of every computer.
- **Chapter 13** — The cache is a temporal-locality bet on how loops
  reuse data. A cache is useful only because loops repeat.
- **Chapter 14** — The REPL is a loop: read, eval, print, loop.
- **Chapter 15** — The OS scheduler loop. The event loop. The network
  packet loop. Every server is a loop.
- **Chapter 16** — The transformer inference loop (one token per
  turn). The training loop (one gradient update per turn). The
  competitive-release loop of the whole AI industry.

Sixteen chapters. Sixteen loops. Some in metal, some in code, some in
economics. Same pattern.

## Why the loop wins

Because computers are cheap and time is not. If a task requires doing
one thing a million times, a loop lets a machine do it while a human
does something else. Doing the same thing a million times by hand is
what humans invented computers to avoid.

The loop is the fundamental **amplifier** of a computer. It turns
programmable machinery into practical machinery. A CPU that ran only
one instruction is useless. A CPU that runs the same instruction a
billion times a second is a computer.

## Loops in Motoi Scheme

Motoi Scheme has three main ways to loop, and they are all the same
underneath.

### `let` with `loop` — named let recursion

The most idiomatic Scheme loop:

```
(let loop ((i 0))
  (if (< i 10)
      (begin
        (display i) (newline)
        (loop (+ i 1)))))
```

`loop` is a name for the anonymous function that the `let` creates.
Calling `(loop (+ i 1))` is tail-recursion — the Scheme runtime does
NOT grow the stack. It reuses the same frame. This is called **tail
call optimization** and R7RS Scheme mandates it. Every named-let loop
runs in constant stack.

### Explicit recursion

Recursion is a loop that goes down a tree:

```
(define (sum-list lst)
  (if (null? lst)
      0
      (+ (car lst) (sum-list (cdr lst)))))

(sum-list '(1 2 3 4 5))    ;; => 15
```

This is not tail-recursive as written — the recursive call is inside
an `+`, so the runtime does have to remember to add to the result.
For long lists you would rewrite it tail-recursively:

```
(define (sum-list-tail lst)
  (let loop ((lst lst) (acc 0))
    (if (null? lst)
        acc
        (loop (cdr lst) (+ acc (car lst))))))

(sum-list-tail '(1 2 3 4 5))    ;; => 15
```

Same answer. Constant stack.

### `for-each` and `map` — higher-order loops

Motoi has `for-each` (side-effects, no return) and `map` (returns a
list of results):

```
(for-each display '(a b c d))       ;; prints abcd
(newline)

(map (lambda (x) (* x x)) '(1 2 3 4 5))
;; => (1 4 9 16 25)
```

Both are implemented as tail-recursive loops inside Motoi's runtime.
Same shape. Same optimizations.

### `do` — the C-style loop

Motoi also supports `do`:

```
(do ((i 0 (+ i 1))
     (sum 0 (+ sum i)))
    ((= i 10) sum))
;; => 45  ;; 0+1+2+...+9
```

This is exactly a `for` loop in C or Python. It is syntactic sugar
over a named-let. Some Schemers use it. Others prefer named-let.
Motoi's opinion: named-let is clearer for one-shots, `do` is fine
when you have multiple loop variables.

## Recursion IS iteration

In Scheme, a tail-recursive procedure is compiled/interpreted into an
iterative loop. There is no performance penalty. There is no stack
growth. Recursion and iteration are the same thing at the
implementation level, once tail-call optimization is in play.

That is a huge idea from SICP (chapter 1). It means you can think in
whichever style — recursion or iteration — feels natural for the
problem, and get the same efficient code either way.

## Loops in the hardware

Every counter (chapter 9) is a hardware loop. Every state machine
(chapter 10) has a loop in its driver. Every CPU (chapter 12) has
the fetch-decode-execute loop. Every DRAM refresh cycle is a loop.
Every network protocol has retransmission loops.

The clock itself is a loop — an oscillator that swings between two
voltages billions of times per second. Without the clock, no
sequential circuit works. **Everything sequential is a loop.**

## The training loop

Every LLM (chapter 16, Book of ML) is trained by a loop:

```
   FOR each batch of training examples:
     forward-pass the batch through the model
     compute the loss (how wrong the model was)
     back-propagate the loss to get gradients
     update the parameters (gradient descent)
   END FOR
```

This loop runs for millions to billions of iterations. It shrinks a
random initial model down onto a corpus by making thousands of
gradient steps per second. All the intelligence of a modern LLM
comes from that loop, executed at enormous scale.

Book of ML chapter 10 walks the training loop step by step and
implements it in Motoi Scheme. If you want to see the code, that is
where to go.

## The inference loop

Every generation of a token from an LLM is a loop:

```
   Start with the prompt tokens.
   FOR each new token to generate:
     forward-pass the sequence through the model
     sample the next token from the output distribution
     append it to the sequence
   END FOR
```

Every token you see stream out of a chat interface is one turn of
this loop.

## The event loop

Every modern GUI, every browser, every server is built on an **event
loop**:

```
   FOREVER:
     wait for an event (keyboard, mouse, network, timer)
     dispatch it to the right handler
     handler runs, possibly emits new events
     back to wait
```

Same loop as the CPU's fetch-decode-execute at a much higher level of
abstraction. Same shape. Different substrate.

## The training-industry loop

Zooming out further: the whole AI industry is itself a loop.

- A lab releases a model.
- Users adopt it.
- Users find its limits.
- The lab collects data on those limits.
- The lab trains a better model.
- Competing labs learn from the release.
- Everybody's next model is a little better.

This has been running since roughly 2018 and shows no sign of
stopping. It is a loop at the civilizational scale.

## Loops are not always what you want

A tight loop is a loop. A recursive tree walk is also a loop. But
sometimes what you want is NOT a loop.

- **Combinational logic** (chapters 5, 6, 11) doesn't loop. It just
  computes.
- **Pure functions** don't loop. They map input to output.
- **Comprehensions and streams** hide loops behind higher-level
  operations. Sometimes clearer.

Every so often you write a program that has no loops — a
straight-line calculation. Those are fine. But most useful programs
loop. Because most useful work is repetitive.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

The loop is the biggest pattern in computer science. It shows up:

- In silicon (feedback wires, clocks, counters).
- In assembly (branches back to earlier addresses).
- In high-level languages (`for`, `while`, recursion, `map`).
- In runtimes (event loops, scheduler loops).
- In hardware/software co-design (CPU cycles).
- In training and inference of LLMs.
- In the history and economics of the whole industry.

Every one of them is a place where a thing happens over and over,
usually with a small change each time, and the accumulated result is
something bigger than any single step.

You could write a whole book about loops and never leave the topic.
This book has, in a sense, done exactly that — sixteen chapters and
seven other appendices, and every one of them was about a loop.

## The final loop

Reading a book is a loop. Read a page. Turn the page. Read the next
page. Repeat until done.

You have reached the end of Appendix E. Now loop back to the front
and pick another appendix.
")
